{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2014}} The '''Ontario Arts Council''' ('''OAC''') is a publicly funded Canadian organization in the province of [[Ontario]] whose purpose is to promote and assist the development of the arts for the enjoyment and benefit of all Ontarians. Based in [[Toronto]], OAC was founded in 1963 by Ontario's [[Premier (Canada)|Premier]] at the time, [[John Robarts]].<ref>[http://www.arts.on.ca/site4.aspx Ontario Arts Council website] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131030131950/http://www.arts.on.ca/site4.aspx |date=30 October 2013 }}</ref>
OAC plays a vital role in fostering the stability and growth of Ontario's arts community. An arm's-length agency of the [[Ministry of Culture (Ontario)|Ministry of Culture]], OAC offers more than fifty funding programs for Ontario-based artists and arts organizations. Grants provide assistance for a specific activity, support for a period of time, or for ongoing operations. OAC administers the Premier's Awards for Excellence in the Arts,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://news.ontario.ca/opo/en/2015/10/winners-announced-for-premiers-awards-for-excellence-in-the-arts.html|title=Winners Announced for Premier's Awards for Excellence in the Arts|date=12 October 2015|work=News release|publisher=[[Queen's Printer for Ontario]]|accessdate=3 November 2015}}</ref> offers additional prizes as well as scholarships from private funds, and further supports Ontario's arts community by conducting research and statistical analyses of the arts and culture. OAC staff manage granting programs, while a 12-member volunteer board of directors oversees the fulfilment of the organization's mandate. The board of directors is appointed by the [[Government of Ontario]] for a three-year term (and may be re-appointed for one additional term).
OAC provides grants in three ways:
* Artistic discipline: [[crafts]], dance, theatre, literature; music; [[visual arts|visual]] and [[media arts]]. * Artistic or other activity: arts education; [[community arts]]; touring; residencies; and capacity building/professional development. * Cultural practice: [[Native American art|Aboriginal Arts]] and [[Franco-Ontarian]] Arts.
